Introduction

Introduction to the topic and motivation

Prostate Cancer is the most common cancer among men. According to the American Cancer Society, about 1 in 9 men will be diagnosed with prostate cancer during their lifetime. It is more likely to occur in African-American men, and approximately 6 out of 10 cases are diagnosed at age 65 or older. Prostate cancer is rare in men under the age of 40.

In addition, prostate cancer is the second leading cause of cancer-related death among men in America, behind lung cancer. About 1 in 41 men will die from prostate cancer.

Prostate-Specific Antigen (PSA) is an enzyme found in men’s blood, produced exclusively by prostate cells. An abnormal rise in PSA levels can indicate prostate cancer. Elevated PSA levels in the blood may occur as prostate cancer cells proliferate in an uncontrolled manner.

In this project, PSA levels are predicted using multiple linear regression, and the association between PSA levels and predictor variables is explored.

Introduction to the dataset

The dataset was obtained from The Elements of Statistical Learning. It contains 97 observations (men) diagnosed with prostate cancer. The predictor variables are shown below. data

  • LPSA: Log PSA level
  • LProWeight: log prostate weight
  • age: age of patient
  • weight: log prostate weight
  • age: age of patient
  • LBPH: Log of the amount of benign prostatic hyperplasia
  • SemVeInv: seminal vesicle invasion
  • LCanVol: log of cancer volume
  • Gleason: Gleason score
  • PerGG: percent of Gleason scores 4 or 5

Aims

The purpose of the data analysis is to predict the PSA level with multiple predictor variables. And the second goal is to estimate the \(\beta_i\) coefficients to discover association between PSA level and other predictor variables.

Statistical Model

We use a multiple linear regression model. \(Y_i\) Log PSA level
\(X_i1\) log prostate weight
\(X_i2\) age of patient
\(X_i3\) log prostate weight
\(X_i4\) age of patient
\(X_i5\) Log of the amount of benign prostatic hyperplasia
\(X_i6\) seminal vesicle invasion
\(X_i7\) log of capsular penetration
\(X_i8\) Gleason score
\(X_i9\) percent of Gleason scores 4 or 5

This model is being considered for the first time \[Y_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X_{1} + \beta_2 X_{2} + \beta_3 X_{3} + \beta_4 X_{4} + \beta_5 X_{5} + \beta_6 X_{6} + \beta_7 X_{7} + \beta_8 X_{8} + \beta_9X_{9} + \epsilon_i\]

Where \(\epsilon_i \sim iidN(0, \sigma^2)\), This is a 97x9 matrix.

Define the model

Model selection

Automatic variable selection is employed to identify the best parsimonious model which should be considered.
Three criterion are considered for the model selection. They consist of \(C_p, BIC, adjR^2\).

The plots indicate that Model 2 & 3 would be great for the predicting the response variable. And when Anova analysis is performed, the other variable such as Age, LBPH, SemVeInv, LCanVol and Gleason are not statistically significant. Therefore, the final model is below.

\(Y_i\) LPSA: Log PSA level
\(X_i1\) LBPH: Log of the amount of benign prostatic hyperplasia
\(X_i2\) SemVeInv: Seminal vesicle invasion

This is the final model is considered.
\[\hat{Y} = 0.16157 + 0.35051X_{1} + 0.50331X_{2} + Error\]

Anova analysis is performed to display statistically significant variables using F-test. As it displays, Age, LBPH, SemVeInv, LProweight, Gleason and PerGG variables don’t have statistically significant.

Model diagnosis

There are not any abnormality found in the plots. There doesn’t appear to be multicollinearity and other violation of linear regression assumptions.

Fit the model to the test dataset for the validation

MSPR is used to evaluate the prediction.

\[MSPR = \sum(Y_i - \hat{Y_i})^2 / n^* \] \(n^*\) = the number of caeses in the validation dataset. The MSPR in this model is 1.264677e-29, which is quite small.
